In [[law]], a '''chambers''' is a room or office used by barristers or a judge. A '''barrister's chambers''' or '''barristers' chambers''' are the rooms used by a barrister or a group of barristers. A '''judge's chambers''', on the other hand, is the office of a [[judge]], where the judge may hear certain types of cases, instead of in open court.

== Judge's chambers ==

A judge's chambers is the office of a judge, where certain types of matters can be heard "in chambers", also known as ''[[in camera]]'', rather than [[in open court]]. Generally, cases heard in chambers are cases, or parts of cases, in which the public and press are not allowed to observe the procedure.<ref name= Amo>{{Citation | first = Eugene | last = Ehrlich | title = Amo, Amas, Amat and More | page = 151 | ISBN = 0-06-272017-1}}.</ref> Judge's chambers are often located on upper floors of the [[court house]], away from the [[courtroom]]s, sometimes in groupings of judge's chambers.<ref>{{cite book|title=Designing Commercial Interiors|pages=338|last=Piotrowski|first=C M|last2=Rogers|first2=E A|location=New Jersey, USA|year=2013|isbn=9781118656976|publisher=John Wiley & Sons}}</ref>

In some jurisdictions, a courtroom, rather than the judge's actual chambers, are used to hear matters "in chambers". Such courtrooms may also be called "chambers".

== Barristers' chambers ==

In [[England and Wales]], [[New Zealand]], Australia, India, Pakistan and Hong Kong, chambers may refer to the office premises used by a [[barrister]] or to a group of barristers, especially in the [[Inns of Court]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.venables.co.uk/bar.htm | title=Barristers' Chambers in England and Wales | publisher=Legal Resources in UK and Ireland| accessdate=4 October 2011 | author=Venables, Delia}}</ref> To share costs and expenses, barristers typically operate fraternally with each other, as [[unincorporated association]]s known as "chambers". The term "Chambers" is used to refer both to the physical premises where the Barrister's Set conduct most of their work from., as well as the 'set' or unincorporated association itself. Most prosperous Chambers typically have office spaces for the barristers to work from, conference rooms with infrastructure to conduct video conferencing for a large audience, printing and photocopying sections, a substantially large and updated [[Library]], as well as rooms for the Barristers' and clients' dining and entertainment. Most Chambers have a staff to look after administrative matters, including a full-fledged kitchen and dining hall to serve up meals and refreshments. The transactional side of chambers are administered by [[barristers' clerk]]s who receive cases from [[Solicitor]]s and agree on matters such as fees on behalf of their employers; they then provide case details to the barristers and conduct office management for them.<ref name="Griffiths-Baker">{{cite book|title=Serving Two Masters: Conflicts of Interest in the Modern Law Firm|last=Griffiths-Baker|first=Janine|pages=51–52|chapter=The Modern Fiduciary: Conflicts in Other Professions|publisher= Hart Publishing|isbn=9781841132297|year=2002|location=Oregon, USA}}</ref> Some chambers specialise in particular areas of law. Members are known as tenants, and can only be dismissed for gross misconduct. 

There are chambers all over England and Wales; however, the largest concentration of them is in [[London]].<ref name="Griffiths-Baker"/> A report by the [[General Council of the Bar]] in 2006, showed that of the 355 practising chambers in the [[United Kingdom]], 210 were based in London.<ref>{{cite book|title=Criminal Justice in England and the United States|pages=166|last=Herschel|first=David|last2=Wakefield|first2=William|last3=Sasse|first3=Scott|publisher=Jones and Bartlett|location=MA, USA|year=2007|isbn=9780763741129}}</ref> 

In Hong Kong, the 133 chambers within the [[Special administrative regions of China|special administrative region]] are almost exclusively located in the [[Victoria, Hong Kong|City of Victoria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://barlist.hkba.org/hkba/ChambersEN/Chambers.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-02-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122100845/http://barlist.hkba.org/hkba/ChambersEN/Chambers.htm |archivedate=22 January 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>

