'''Varatuomari''' (lit. "vice-judge", Swedish: ''vicehäradshövding'') or '''Master in Law with court training'''<ref>http://www.lakimiesliitto.fi/julkaisut/muutjulkaisut/lakimiesnimikkeet/  {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402091910/http://www.lakimiesliitto.fi/julkaisut/muutjulkaisut/lakimiesnimikkeet/ |date=2015-04-02 }}</ref> or '''trained on the bench''' is a [[Finland|Finnish]] legal title. The degree consists of a [[Master of Laws|master's degree in law]] and one year of [[court]] training as a Trainee District Judge in a [[district court]], usually done very soon after graduation. The title is granted by the local [[Appellate court|appeals court,]] on a recommendation of the chief judge (''[[lawspeaker|laamanni]]''). Thus, it can be considered a specially regulated [[Externship#Legal Externships|legal externship]]. Officially, the degree is no longer a formal requirement to any state office, but it remains a ''[[de facto]]'' requirement for applying into the positions of a [[judge]] or a [[prosecutor]], and is usually held also by [[Defense attorney|defense attorneys]]. It is recognized as a relevant master's degree for purposes of police officer promotions.

